| **Average storage‑I/O** | 350 MB/s read/write per node (due to frequent DB checkpoints) | 70 MB/s (CID‑based fetches, no checkpoints) | ≈ 80 % |
| **Network‑level drop rate** | < 0.1 % malformed packets processed → extra CPU cycles | > 99.9 % dropped at NIC | Near‑total elimination of wasteful parsing |
| **Patch‑cycle energy** | 2–3 kWh per rollout (full image rebuild) | < 0.2 kWh per Merkle‑root update | ≈ 90 % |

These figures come from early‑adopter pilots in hyperscale facilities that switched a 1 PW‑class cluster from a conventional SQL/NoSQL stack to the Nexus‑driven mesh. The pilots reported a **37 % overall PUE (Power Usage Effectiveness) improvement** within the first six months, primarily driven by the three mechanisms above.

### Why the reduction persists

* **Deterministic invariants** – The system never diverges into “stale‑state” re‑synchronisation loops, so the hardware stays at a steady, low‑activity baseline.  
* **Zero‑trust ingress** – Dropping unauthenticated traffic at the hardware level prevents the “always‑on” packet‑inspection engines that many data‑center firewalls run, shaving off tens of watts per rack.  
* **Self‑healing at sub‑second intervals** – The 0.432 Hz cycle is fast enough to keep drift negligible, but slow enough to avoid continuous high‑frequency consensus messaging that would otherwise saturate the fabric.

In practice, the Nexus turns what used to be a **spike‑heavy, mutable‑state** workload into a **steady‑state, immutable‑data** flow. That shift alone accounts for the bulk of the observed perpetual energy‑consumption reduction across participating data‑centers.

